Node Classification with Graph Neural Networks

Following our previous tutorial in GNNs, we covered how to create graph neural networks.

In this tutorial, we will be learning how to use Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) for node classification. Given the ground-truth labels of only a small subset of nodes, and want to infer the labels for all the remaining nodes (transductive learning).

``` ## Import

@raw html <div class="markdown"> <p>Let us start off by importing some libraries. We will be using Flux.jl and <code>GraphNeuralNetworks.jl</code> for our tutorial.</p></div></body></HTML>

Visualize

We want to visualize the the outputs of the resutls using t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (tsne) to embed our output embeddings onto a 2D plane.

function visualize_tsne(out, targets)
    z = tsne(out, 2)
    scatter(z[:, 1], z[:, 2], color=Int.(targets[1:size(z,1)]), leg = false)
end

``` ## Dataset: Cora

@raw html <div class="markdown"> <p>For our tutorial, we will be using the <code>Cora</code> dataset. <code>Cora</code> is a citaton network of 2708 documents classified into one of seven classes and 5429 links. Each node represent articles/documents and the edges between these nodes if one of them cite each other.</p><p>Each publication in the dataset is described by a 0/1-valued word vector indicating the absence/presence of the corresponding word from the dictionary. The dictionary consists of 1433 unique words.</p><p>This dataset was first introduced by <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1603.08861">Yang et al. (2016)</a> as one of the datasets of the <code>Planetoid</code> benchmark suite. We will be using <a href="https://juliaml.github.io/MLDatasets.jl/stable/">MLDatasets.jl</a> for an easy accss to this dataset.</p></div></body></HTML>

Multi-layer Perception Network (MLP)

In theory, we should be able to infer the category of a document solely based on its content, i.e. its bag-of-words feature representation, without taking any relational information into account.

Let's verify that by constructing a simple MLP that solely operates on input node features (using shared weights across all nodes):

begin
    struct MLP
        layers::NamedTuple
    end

    Flux.@functor MLP
    
    function MLP(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels; drop_rate=0.5)
        layers = (hidden = Dense(num_features => hidden_channels),
                    drop = Dropout(drop_rate),
                    classifier = Dense(hidden_channels => num_classes))
        return MLP(layers)
    end

    function (model::MLP)(x::AbstractMatrix)
        l = model.layers
        x = l.hidden(x)
        x = relu(x)
        x = l.drop(x)
        x = l.classifier(x)
        return x
    end
end

Training a Multilayer Perceptron

Our MLP is defined by two linear layers and enhanced by ReLU non-linearity and Dropout. Here, we first reduce the 1433-dimensional feature vector to a low-dimensional embedding (hidden_channels=16), while the second linear layer acts as a classifier that should map each low-dimensional node embedding to one of the 7 classes.

Let's train our simple MLP by following a similar procedure as described in the first part of this tutorial. We again make use of the cross entropy loss and Adam optimizer. This time, we also define a accuracy function to evaluate how well our final model performs on the test node set (which labels have not been observed during training).

function train(model::MLP, data::AbstractMatrix, epochs::Int, opt, ps)
    Flux.trainmode!(model)

    for epoch in 1:epochs
        loss, gs = Flux.withgradient(ps) do
            ŷ = model(data)
            logitcrossentropy(ŷ[:, train_mask], y[:, train_mask])
        end
    
        Flux.Optimise.update!(opt, ps, gs)
        if epoch % 200 == 0
            @show epoch, loss
        end
    end
end
train (generic function with 1 method)
function accuracy(model::MLP, x::AbstractMatrix, y::Flux.OneHotArray, mask::BitVector)
    Flux.testmode!(model)
    mean(onecold(model(x))[mask] .== onecold(y)[mask])
end
accuracy (generic function with 1 method)
begin
    mlp = MLP(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels)
    ps_mlp = Flux.params(mlp)
    opt_mlp = ADAM(1e-3)
    epochs = 2000
    train(mlp, g.ndata.features, epochs, opt_mlp, ps_mlp)
end

After training the model, we can call the accuracy function to see how well our model performs on unseen labels. Here, we are interested in the accuracy of the model, i.e., the ratio of correctly classified nodes:

accuracy(mlp, g.ndata.features, y, .!train_mask)
0.4127725856697819

As one can see, our MLP performs rather bad with only about 47% test accuracy. But why does the MLP do not perform better? The main reason for that is that this model suffers from heavy overfitting due to only having access to a small amount of training nodes, and therefore generalizes poorly to unseen node representations.

It also fails to incorporate an important bias into the model: Cited papers are very likely related to the category of a document. That is exactly where Graph Neural Networks come into play and can help to boost the performance of our model.

``` ## Training a Graph Convolutional Neural Network (GNN)

@raw html <div class="markdown"> <p>We can easily convert our MLP to a GNN by swapping the <code>torch.nn.Linear</code> layers with PyG's GNN operators.</p><p>Following-up on <a href="">the first part of this tutorial</a>, we replace the linear layers by the <a href=""><code>GCNConv</code></a> module. To recap, the <strong>GCN layer</strong> (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1609.02907">Kipf et al. (2017)</a>) is defined as</p><p class="tex">$\mathbf{x}_v^{(\ell + 1)} = \mathbf{W}^{(\ell + 1)} \sum_{w \in \mathcal{N}(v) \, \cup \, \{ v \}} \frac{1}{c_{w,v}} \cdot \mathbf{x}_w^{(\ell)}$</p><p>where <span class="tex">$\mathbf{W}^{(\ell + 1)}$</span> denotes a trainable weight matrix of shape <code>[numoutputfeatures, numinputfeatures]</code> and <span class="tex">$c_{w,v}$</span> refers to a fixed normalization coefficient for each edge. In contrast, a single <code>Linear</code> layer is defined as</p><p class="tex">$\mathbf{x}_v^{(\ell + 1)} = \mathbf{W}^{(\ell + 1)} \mathbf{x}_v^{(\ell)}$</p><p>which does not make use of neighboring node information.</p></div></body></HTML>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin struct GCN layers::NamedTuple end

Flux.@functor GCN # provides parameter collection, gpu movement and more



function GCN(num_features, num_classes, hidden_channels; drop_rate=0.5)
    layers = (conv1 = GCNConv(num_features =&gt; hidden_channels),
                drop = Dropout(drop_rate), 
                conv2 = GCNConv(hidden_channels =&gt; num_classes))
    return GCN(layers)
end

function (gcn::GCN)(g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix)
    l = gcn.layers
    x = l.conv1(g, x)
    x = relu.(x)
    x = l.drop(x)
    x = l.conv2(g, x)
    return x
end

end</code></pre> <!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body></body></HTML>

end</code></pre> <!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body><img <!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body><div class="markdown"><p>We certainly can do better by training our model. The training and testing procedure is once again the same, but this time we make use of the node features <code>x</code><strong>and</strong> the graph <code>g</code> as input to our GCN model.</p></div></body></HTML>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function train(model::GCN, g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix, epochs::Int, ps, opt) Flux.trainmode!(model)

for epoch in 1:epochs
    loss, gs = Flux.withgradient(ps) do
        ŷ = model(g, x)
        logitcrossentropy(ŷ[:,train_mask], y[:,train_mask])
    end

    Flux.Optimise.update!(opt, ps, gs)
    if epoch % 200 == 0
        @show epoch, loss
    end
end

end </code></pre> <!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body><pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-train">train (generic function with 2 methods)</pre></body></HTML>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function accuracy(model::GCN, g::GNNGraph, x::AbstractMatrix, y::Flux.OneHotArray, mask::BitVector) Flux.testmode!(model) mean(onecold(model(g, x))[mask] .== onecold(y)[mask]) end</code></pre> <!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body><pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-accuracy">accuracy (generic function with 2 methods)</pre></body></HTML>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin psgcn = Flux.params(gcn) optgcn = ADAM(1e-2) train(gcn, g, x, epochs, psgcn, optgcn) end</code></pre> <!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body></body></HTML>

<!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body><div class="markdown"><p>Now let's evaluate the loss of our trained GCN.</p></div></body></HTML>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>withterminal() do trainaccuracy = accuracy(gcn, g, g.ndata.features, y, trainmask) testaccuracy = accuracy(gcn, g, g.ndata.features, y, .!train_mask)

println("Train accuracy: $(train_accuracy)")
println("Test accuracy: $(test_accuracy)")

end</code></pre> <!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body><pre id="plutouiterminal">Train accuracy: 1.0 Test accuracy: 0.7441588785046729 </pre></body></HTML>

<!DOCTYPE ><HTML><head></head><body><div class="markdown"><p><strong>There it is!</strong> By simply swapping the linear layers with GNN layers, we can reach <strong>75.77% of test accuracy</strong>! This is in stark contrast to the 59% of test accuracy obtained by our MLP, indicating that relational information plays a crucial role in obtaining better performance.</p><p>We can also verify that once again by looking at the output embeddings of our trained model, which now produces a far better clustering of nodes of the same category.</p></div></body></HTML>

out_trained = gcn(g, x) |&gt; transpose
visualize_tsne(out_trained, g.ndata.targets)

(Optional) Exercises

  1. To achieve better model performance and to avoid overfitting, it is usually a good idea to select the best model based on an additional validation set.

The Cora dataset provides a validation node set as g.ndata.val_mask, but we haven't used it yet. Can you modify the code to select and test the model with the highest validation performance? This should bring test performance to 82% accuracy.

  1. How does GCN behave when increasing the hidden feature dimensionality or the number of layers?

Does increasing the number of layers help at all?

  1. You can try to use different GNN layers to see how model performance changes. What happens if you swap out all GCNConv instances with GATConv layers that make use of attention? Try to write a 2-layer GAT model that makes use of 8 attention heads in the first layer and 1 attention head in the second layer, uses a dropout ratio of 0.6 inside and outside each GATConv call, and uses a hidden_channels dimensions of 8 per head.
